ce:section.ce:para:
The analytical performance of the opposed fluorescent probe was investigated by analysis of various concentrations of DA in ultrapure water. Fig. 4
                        a showed the fluorescence spectra of the S,N-CQDs in the presence of different concentrations of DA. Specifically, the fluorescence intensity of S,N-CQDs gradually decreased with the progressively increasing concentration of DA. And the fluorescence emission of S,N-CQDs aqueous solution gradually changed from bright blue to dark blue under 365 nm UV lamp (Fig. 4a, insert). More importantly, a good linear relationship was obtained in the DA concentration range of 0−50 μM (Fig. 4b). The equation is F0/F = 1.004 + 0.027C[DA], with a correlation coefficient of 0.991 (R2 = 0.991), and the limit of detection (LOD) was measured to be 0.082 μM based on three times the standard deviation. Compared with recently published assays [56–61], the S,N-CQDs in this work gave a relatively lower LOD and wider linear range (listed in Table 1
                        ). To assess the specificity of the S,N-CQDs fluorescent probe to DA, the PL intensity ratio F/F0 of S,N-CQDs aqueous solutions in the absence and presence of different interference was analyzed. As shown in Fig. 4c, the fluorescence quenching degree was only dependent on DA, and the influences of other interference were almost negligible. More importantly, as shown in Fig. S5, S,N-CQDs were more sensitive to DA than N-CQDs, probably because the double element doping can introduce more active sites and hydrophilic functional groups to respond to dopamine. The above results showed that the proposed dual-element doped S,N-CQDs fluorescent probe had excellent detection performance for DA.
